## AppThemeBinding — Automatic Light/Dark Mode

The simplest approach is `AppThemeBinding`, which picks a value based on the device's current system theme. Replace every hardcoded color:

### XAML

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=White, Dark=#1E1E1E}">

    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="20" Spacing="16">

        <Label Text="Welcome"
               FontSize="24"
               TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#333333, Dark=#F0F0F0}" />

        <Label Text="This page follows the system theme."
               TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#666666, Dark=#AAAAAA}" />

        <Button Text="Get Started"
                BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#2196F3, Dark=#BB86FC}"
                TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=White, Dark=Black}" />

    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

Each `AppThemeBinding` has a `Light` and `Dark` value — the framework selects the right one automatically when the OS theme changes.

### C# Equivalent

Use `SetAppThemeColor` (for colors) or `SetAppTheme<T>` (for any property):

```csharp
var page = new ContentPage();
page.SetAppThemeColor(ContentPage.BackgroundColorProperty, Colors.White, Color.FromArgb("#1E1E1E"));

var title = new Label { Text = "Welcome", FontSize = 24 };
title.SetAppThemeColor(Label.TextColorProperty, Color.FromArgb("#333333"), Color.FromArgb("#F0F0F0"));

var button = new Button { Text = "Get Started" };
button.SetAppThemeColor(Button.BackgroundColorProperty, Color.FromArgb("#2196F3"), Color.FromArgb("#BB86FC"));
button.SetAppThemeColor(Button.TextColorProperty, Colors.White, Colors.Black);
```

### Detecting / Overriding the Theme in Code

```csharp
// Read current theme
AppTheme current = Application.Current!.RequestedTheme;

// Force dark mode (ignores OS setting)
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Follow OS again
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;

// React to changes
Application.Current!.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    // e.RequestedTheme is the new theme
};
```

### ⚠️ Android Gotcha

Ensure your `MainActivity` includes `ConfigChanges.UiMode` — without it, toggling dark mode restarts the activity instead of firing theme-change events:

```csharp
[Activity(ConfigurationChanges = ConfigChanges.ScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Orientation
                               | ConfigChanges.UiMode   // ← required
                               | ConfigChanges.ScreenLayout
                               | ConfigChanges.SmallestScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Density)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

**Quick summary:** `AppThemeBinding` is ideal for straight light/dark support with zero boilerplate. If you later need more than two themes or user-selectable palettes, look into swapping `ResourceDictionary` files with `DynamicResource` bindings.
